elements.name: ROUND-TO-INTEGER
elements.usage: (round number integer) applies Lisp round function on the first parameter, required
elements.description: Round a real number to an integer

elements.name: INTEGER-IN-RANGE
elements.usage:
(integer-in-range integer1 integer2 integer3) is true if
integer1 is in the range [integer2,integer3], i.e., 
integer2<=integer1<=integer3.
This can only be used to generate integer1 from integer2 and integer3.
elements.description: Check if a number is between two other numbers

elements.usage:
(/ number1 number2 number3) is true if number1 / number2 = number3.
This can only be used to generate any of the three arguments from the 
other two.
elements.description: Arithmetic division operator

elements.usage:
(* number1 number2 number3) is true if number1 x number2 = number3.
This can only be used to generate number3 from number1 and number2.
elements.description: Arithmetic multiplication operator

elements.usage:
(+ number1 number2 number3) is true if number1 + number2 = number3.
This can be used to generate any argument given the other two.
elements.description: Arithmetic plus operator

elements.usage:
(<= number1 number2) is true if the first number is less than or equal to
the second.
This can be used for comparing constants to variables, variables to variables,
or contants to constants.
elements.description: Less than or equal Comparison operator

elements.usage:
(>= number1 number2) is true if the first number is greater than or equal 
to the second.
This can be used for comparing constants to variables, variables to variables,
or contants to constants.
elements.description: Greater than or equal Comparison operator

elements.usage:
(< number1 number2) is true if the first number is less than the second.
This can be used for comparing constants to variables, variables to variables,
or contants to constants.
elements.description: Less than Comparison operator

elements.usage:
(> number1 number2) is true if the first number is more than the second.
This can be used for comparing constants to variables, variables to variables,
or contants to constants.
elements.description: Greater than Comparison operator

elements.usage:
(= number1 number2) is true if the two numbers are equal
This can be used for comparing constants to variables, variables to variables,
or contants to constants, but it is typically not needed because one can
simply replace a variable in the query with a constant or another variable.
elements.description: Equality Comparison of numbers

elements.name: BIZFILE-DETAILS
elements.usage:
(bizfile-details id principal-address mailing-address sos-standing ftb-standing agent-standing vcfcf-standing)
 means that https://bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov/search/business, when given
 the ID as input, returns the detailed data for a business with that ID.
 This data is currently not cached.
elements.description: Retrieve details for California business matching unique id

elements.name: BIZFILE-FIND
elements.usage:
(bizfile-find searchfor title id type formedin agent filingdate)
 means that https://bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov/search/business, when given
 the search string as input, returns data for matching businesses.
 This data is currently not cached.
elements.description: Search California business registry for matches

elements.name: CLINICALTRIALS-API-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(clinicaltrials-api-search searchspec study)
means that the api at https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/api/v2/studies
returns the study (as one element of a set), when given as its search
parameters the set of things in the searchspec.  The api is described at
https://www.clinicaltrials.gov/data-about-studies/learn-about-api.
The searchspec is a json encoding of the search parameters.
The resulting studies are similarly represented as json objects.
The api is capable of generating 1000 results at a time and returns
a token that can be used to get more, but that is not used in this
implementation.
This relation can only be accessed by supplying a searchspec and retrieving
a set of studies.
elements.description: Search table for new ct.gov API

elements.name: CLINICALTRIALS-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(clinicaltrials-search searchstring NCTNumber Title URL Acronym
    Status Summary Results Conditions Interventions 
    PrimaryOutcomeMeasures SecondaryOutcomeMeasures OtherOutcomeMeasures
    Sponsor Collaborators Sex Age Phases Enrollment FunderType
    StudyType StudyDesigns OtherIDs StartDate PrimaryCompletionDate
    CompletionDate FirstPosted ResultsFirstPosted LastUpdatePosted
    Locations StudyDocuments)
means that when the search string is used as input to www.clinicaltrials.gov
search, the rest of the arguments are returned as results.  
The only output we claim to understand is the url which leads to data about
a particular study that is considered to be a search result for the input
searchstring.
elements.description: Search table for general ct.gov

elements.name: PHILOSOPHER
elements.description: List of philsophers who are Twitter targets!

elements.name: INDICATION
elements.usage: FAERS data capture of the underlying condition for which drug(s) recommended.
elements.description: FDA data - why drug was prescribe

elements.name: DEMOGRAPHIC
elements.usage: Describes the FDA's patient demographic and administrative data -- one record per
elements.description: FDA data - demographics for an event

elements.name: DRUG
elements.usage: Contains drub/biologic data for as many medications as were reported for the event
elements.description: FDA data - drug data for an event

elements.name: OUTCOME
elements.usage: Contains the outcomes data for an event
elements.description: FDA data - outcome of an event

elements.name: REACTION
elements.usage: Describes the FDA's terms coded for the adverse events for various drugs.
elements.description: FDA data - reaction to a drug

elements.name: OCCP-CODE-INDEX
elements.description: FDA OCCP code

elements.name: AG-CODE-INDEX
elements.description: FDA ag code

elements.name: OT-CODE-INDEX
elements.description: FDA outcome code

elements.name: CURRENCY-CONVERT
elements.usage:
(currency-convert currency1 currency2 date factor) means that one unit of currency1 was worth factor units of currency2 on the given date. The currencies are three letter codes such as USD for US dollar. See relation currency for currency codes.
Date has the form yyyy-mm-dd. Factor is a number, e.g., 1.234 This data comes from http://www.x-rates.com/historical, which seems to have data back to 2005.
Currently this data is not cached at all.
The only way to access this relation is to supply the currencies and date and generate the factor.
elements.description: Currency conversion computation

elements.name: CURRENCY
elements.usage:
(currency code name) means that there is a currency with the given three 
letter code and the given name, e.g., USD and US Dollar.
This data comes from http://www.x-rates.com/historical and is read
only at server startup.

elements.name: INFLATION
elements.usage:
(inflation year1 year2 factor) means that one dollar in year1 is
 worth factor dollars in year2.  The years are numbers like 1995 and
 the factor is a number like 2.5.
  The only way to access this relation is to supply year1 and year2
 and find factor.
 Data in this relation are only added, never revised or deleted.  
 Non-empty results are cached indefinitely and cache controls are ignored.
elements.description: Inflation calculation for the US dollar

elements.name: GOVTRACK
elements.usage:
(govtrack searchstring bill-url name sponsor status) means that www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/subjects/agriculture_and_food/5816 when asked to find searchstring returns an entry with the bill with the given url (which describes the bill), name, sponsor and status.
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchstring. The data retrieved are currently not cached.

elements.name: NCSL-HEMP-STATUTES
elements.usage:
(ncsl-hemp-statutes state statutes)
shows data from the table at
http://www.ncsl.org/research/agriculture-and-rural-development/state-industrial-hemp-statutes.aspx
where state is the state name in the first column and statutes is
the text in the second column (which we don't know how to separate
into individual statutes)

elements.name: NCSL-HEMP-SUMMARY
elements.usage:
(ncsl-hemp-statutes state summary)
shows data from the table at
http://www.ncsl.org/research/agriculture-and-rural-development/state-industrial-hemp-statutes.aspx
where state is the state name in the first column and summary is
one of the items in the text in the third column

elements.name: CLINICALTRIALS-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(clinicaltrials-search searchstring NCTNumber Title URL Acronym
    Status Summary Results Conditions Interventions 
    PrimaryOutcomeMeasures SecondaryOutcomeMeasures OtherOutcomeMeasures
    Sponsor Collaborators Sex Age Phases Enrollment FunderType
    StudyType StudyDesigns OtherIDs StartDate PrimaryCompletionDate
    CompletionDate FirstPosted ResultsFirstPosted LastUpdatePosted
    Locations StudyDocuments)
means that when the search string is used as input to www.clinicaltrials.gov
search, the rest of the arguments are returned as results.  
The only output we claim to understand is the url which leads to data about
a particular study that is considered to be a search result for the input
searchstring.
elements.description: Search table for general ct.gov

elements.name: DRUG-SIDE-EFFECT
elements.usage:
(drug-side-effect drug category symptom)
 is true if https://www.drugs.com/sfx/[drug]-side-effects.html lists symptom
 under the given category (serious, other, professionals) meaning serious
 symptoms (see doctor immediately), other symptoms and descriptions for
 professionals, which tend to include frequency information.
 All of the parameters are strings.
 This relation can only be accessed by supplying the drug name as input.
elements.description: Look up drugs.com for drug symptom

elements.name: PUBMED-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(pubmed-search query title authors journal details pmid)
 is true if a pubmed (www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed) search for the query string
 returns, among its first 20 results, one with the given title, authors, etc.
 All of the parameters are strings.  The details seems to contain things like
 date and page numbers (not clear how to parse it).  The pmid seems to be
 an id for this record and can be used to construct the link to the article
 at pubmed (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/[pmid]) and also to a link 
 to similar articles
 (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?linkname=pubmed_pubmed&from_uid=[pmid]).
 This relation can only be accessed by supplying the query string as input.
elements.description: Medical literature search at pubmed

elements.name: DRUG-GENERIC-COMMON-BRAND
elements.usage:
(drug-generic-common-brand genericname brandname)
 uses google search to find the common brand names with the given generic
 drug name.  The generic name is required as input.
 The data that is found is cached for the life of the running server,
 since we don't expect this data to change.  However queries that don't
 find any results are not cached.
 Both of the parameters are strings.
 The implementation relies on the fact that (at least currently) when the
 search query is the generic name of a drug, the relevant data appears on
 the right side of the google result page with various labels that we
 assume to be used only for describing drugs.
elements.description: Eumerate brand names corresponding to named generic drug

elements.name: DRUG-BRAND-GENERIC
elements.usage:
(drug-brand-generic brandname genericname drugclass)
 is intended to find the generic name of a drug from its brand name.
 The brand name is required as input and from this the generic name is
 generated, along with the drug class (like antibiotic).
 The data that is found is cached for the life of the running server,
 since we don't expect this data to change.  However queries that don't
 find any results are not cached.
 All of the parameters are strings.
 The implementation currently does a simple google search for the
 brand name, relying on the fact that (at least currently) when the
 search query is the name of a drug, the relevant data appears on the
 right side of the google result page with various labels that we assume
 to be used only for describing drugs.
elements.description: Search for generic drug name for a branded drug

elements.name: YELP
elements.usage:
(yelp searchfor location name address lat lon rating nreviews) means that http://www.yelp.com, when asked to find searchfor (such as hospital, pizza, ymca ...) near location (a zip code, city, or even an entire address), returns, among the first 10 (?) results, one with the given name, address, etc. Lat and lon are the latitude and longitude, rating is the average rating (# stars, e.g., 3.5), nreviews is the number of reviews.
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchfor and location. The rest is generated by constructing, retrieving and reading the url. Data retrieved is cached and reused for 30 days.
elements.description: YELP.com directory of vendors

elements.name: YELLOWPAGES
elements.usage:
(yellowpages searchfor location name address city state zip miles lat lon) means that http://www.yellowpages.com, when asked to find searchfor (such as hospital, pizza, ymca ...) near location (a zip code, city, or even an entire address), returns, among the closest 30 results, one with the given name, address, city, state, and zip code. Miles is the number of miles from the given location, lat and lon are the latitude and longitude.
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchfor and location. The rest is generated by constructing, retrieving and reading the url. The data retrieved are cached and reused for 30 days.
elements.description: YP.com directory of vendors

elements.name: GOOGLEMAPS-URL
elements.usage:
(googlemaps-url lattitute longitude url)
means that the url shows a google map with the location at the given lattitude
and logitude marked.  The url is computed from the lattitude and longitude.
Lattitude and longitude are numbers of degrees.
elements.description: Mapping URL from Google

elements.name: GEODISTANCE
elements.usage:
(geodistance latitude1 longitude1 latitude2 longitude2 km mi) is true if the distance (as the crow flies, ignoring elevation) between the two locations identified by (latitude1, longitude1) and (latitude2, longitude2) is km kilometers, which is the same as mi miles. The latitudes and longitudes are numbers of degrees.
We use as the radius of the earth 6378 km, 3963.2 mi.
elements.description: Compute distance between 2 points

elements.name: WEBGIS
elements.usage:
(webgis streetaddr city state zip latitude longitude score geotype)
means that lookup of streetaddr,city,state,zip (all text strings)
at webgis.usc.edu returns the given latitude, longitude, score, type, geotype.
The state should be a 2 character state code.  Latitude and longitude are
floating point numbers.  The other outputs are described at
http://webgis.usc.edu/Services/Geocode/WebService/GeocoderWebService.aspx:
Score is a percentage describing how well the input matches the address found
and may be interpreted as the likelihood that the correct object has been 
found.  Geotype is a text string indicating the size of the object found.
Parcel means a single address, ZCTA means a zip code.  Other possible values
include city, state and unknown.  The coordinates are generally the at the
center of the given object.
Any of the inputs can be empty, but this is likely to result in worse results.
elements.description: Provides geo coding from address to lat/long and vice versa

elements.name: FOITEXT
elements.usage: FDA MAUDE (medical device) database table foitext

elements.usage: (quandl-search query database_code dataset_code) is true if a QUANDL search for the query string returns, amongs its results, the database and dataset codes.  These then have to be used in subsequent searches to get the actual data for a given database_code/dataset_code.  The query string can have multiple keywords with + in between them for a conjunctive search for all keywords

elements.name: QUANDL-METADATA

elements.usage:
(ong-twitter-influencer name twitterhandle description) describes those
listed as Influencers to follow in the Oil and Gas sector at https://www.oilandgasiq.com/strategy-management-and-information/articles/twitter-oil-gas .
elements.description: Data for oil and gas influencers

elements.name: SURGE
elements.description: Surge at a given PSAP system as a whole

elements.name: REQUEST-RESOLUTION
elements.description: Resolution of an earlier Procurement request

elements.name: REQUEST-ARRIVAL
elements.description: Table of Procurement requests at a PSAP

elements.usage: The different types of 9-1-1 request resolutions
elements.description: Enumerated ways to resolve a Procurement request

elements.name: REQUEST-TYPE
elements.usage: The different types of Procurement requests
elements.description: Enumerated types of Procurement requests

elements.name: CSIMARKET-CUSTOMER
elements.usage:
(csimarket-customer searchsymbol name symbol market-cap revenue income employees) means that https://csimarket.com/stocks/markets_glance.php, given the search symbol (the symbol for a company) shows in the list of customers of the company with the given name and symbol (strings). Market-cap, revenue and income are numeric (millions of dollars?), as is employees (number of employees).
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchstring. The data retrieved are currently not cached.
elements.description: List customers of a company by symbol

elements.name: CSIMARKET-COMPETITION
elements.usage:
(csimarket-competition searchsymbol competitor revenues marketshare) means that https://csimarket.com/stocks/competitionSEG2.php?code=[searchsymbol] (search symbol is the symbol for a company) shows in the list of competitors for the company a row indicating (we THINK) that the company named competitor had revenues (in dollars) in the previous year and a market share of marketshare (percent). That page can show several tables for different parts of the business, but our results only show the first table, which we think is for the business as a whole. The results include the company identified by the search symbol.
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchstring. The data retrieved are currently not cached.
elements.description: List competitors of a company by symbol

elements.name: SEC-DOC-FILING-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(sec-doc-filing-search docslink searchterm htmldocname occurs)
  means that the documents listed at docslink (at http://www.sec.gov )contain the searchterm
  'occurs' number of times in the specific document at 'htmldocname'

elements.name: SEC
elements.usage:
(sec company-symbol filing-type docs description date file-film) means that https://www.sec.gov/cgi-bin/browse-edgar shows for the given company symbol a filing of the given type on the given date. It also shows for that filing the given description, Docs is text containing links relative to https://www.sec.gov. File-film is the last column of the table containing what appear to be two separate id's of some sort.
This data can only be accessed by supplying the searchstring. The data retrieved are currently not cached.
elements.description: SEC filings for a company by its symbol

elements.name: STOCK-SYMBOL
elements.usage:
(stock-symbol exchange symbol companyname)
shows data from the tables at http://eoddata.com/stocklist
The exchanges currently supported are NYSE and NASDAQ.
This data is prefetched at server startup and stored.
elements.description: List of company symbols in different markets

elements.name: EDEN-SENTIMENT
elements.usage:
(eden-sentiment provider text status score sentiment)
  means that Eden's API returns the output status, score, sentiment
  for inputs: provider and text.  The inputs are mandatory for this to work.
elements.description: Use EDEN API to get sentiment scores from engines like Google, Amazon, and others

elements.name: SENTIMENT-CATEGORY
elements.usage: compute sentiment from raw emotion scores in Watson

elements.name: WATSON-EMOTION
elements.usage:
(WatsonEmotion text sadness joy fear disgust anger)
   is true if the IBM Watson NLP API extracts the entity of that name and type
   with the sentiment label and score

elements.name: WATSON-NLP
elements.usage:
(WatsonNLP text name type sentiment score)
   is true if the IBM Watson NLP API extracts the entity of that name and type
   with the sentiment label and score

elements.name: TWEETS-FROM
elements.usage:
(tweets-from userhandle date time message)
means that twitter.com, when asked for messages sent by userhandle, returns 
as one element of the list a tweet with the given date (string of form
 yyyy-mm-dd), time (string of form hh:mm:ss) and message (string).
elements.description: Twitter search by sender of the tweet

elements.name: TWEET-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(tweetsearch keyword date time message sender tweetid)
means that twitter.com, when asked for messages related to keyword, returns as 
one element of the list a tweet with the given date (string of form yyyy-mm-dd),
time (string of form hh:mm:ss), message (string) and sender (string).
elements.description: Twitter search by keyword or topic

elements.name: STARTS-WITH
elements.usage:
(string-contains string1 string2)
  iff string1 starts with string2 (case insensitively)
elements.description: Match a string (case insensitively) at the beginning

elements.name: STRING=
elements.usage:
(string= string1 string2) is true if string2 and string1
are the same (case-sensitive)
elements.description: Case sensitive string equality

elements.name: STRING-CONTAINS-CS
elements.usage:
(string-contains string1 string2)
  iff string2 occurs (case-sensitive) in string1
elements.description: Case sensitive substring check

elements.name: STRING-CONTAINS
elements.usage:
(string-contains string1 string2)
  iff string2 occurs (case-insensitive) in string1
elements.description: Case insensitive substring check

elements.name: STRING-GREATERP
elements.usage:
(string-greaterp string1 string2) is true if string2 comes after 
string1 alphabetically (case-insensitive)

elements.name: STRING-EQUAL
elements.usage:
(string-equal string1 string2) is true if string2 and string1
are the same (case-insensitive)
elements.description: Case insensitive string equality

elements.name: INT-LIST-STRING=
elements.usage:
(int-list-string= string1 string2) is true if its two string arguments
are either equal or can be parsed as equal lists of integers separated by a
single delimiter character.  The delimiter need not be the same in the two
strings but it must be consistent for each string individually.
This is useful for comparing date and time strings, e.g., 2000-01-23 is
equivalent to 2000/1/23 even though one uses leading zeros and they use 
different delimiters.

elements.name: SPLIT2
elements.usage:
(split2 string separator before after) is true if string has the form of before,separator,after where separator does not appear in before. In other words, separator occurs in string, before is the part of string that appears before the first occurrence of separator and after is the part that appears after it.
This is intended for simple parsing, such as 'lastname, firstname'. There are two ways to generate this relation. Either string and separator or separator, before and after must be given as inputs.
Note that if the before string contains the separator, the generator returns no tuples, i.e., there is no string s s.t. (split2 s "," "a,b" "c")

elements.name: PARSE3INTS
elements.usage:
(parse3ints string x y z)
is true if string has the form of three integers, x, y, z, separated by single non-digit characters. The integers must be strings of decimal digits. No signs or leading or trailing whitespace are allowed. This is intended for parsing date and time strings, e.g.
(parse3ints "2009-1-23" 2009 1 23). There are two ways to generate tuples. One is to supply string as input and use it to generate the integers. The alternative is to supply all the integers and generate the string.

elements.name: PARSE2INTS
elements.usage:
(parse2ints string x y)
is true if string has the form of two integers, x, y, separated by single non-digit characters. The integers must be strings of decimal digits. No signs or leading or trailing whitespace are allowed. This is intended for parsing date and time strings, e.g.
(parse2ints "12:15" 12 15). There are two ways to generate tuples. One is to supply string as input and use it to generate the integers. The alternative is to supply all the integers and generate the string.

elements.name: CONCATENATE
elements.usage:
(concatenate first second combined)
  combined results from contatenating first and second with space in between
elements.description: Concatenate strings with space in between

elements.name: DATE-TIME-STRING
elements.usage: (date-time-string ut string) is true when string is the printable version of a universal time, the required first parameter
elements.description: Convert a universal time to a printable string

elements.name: TIME-DIFF
elements.usage:
(time-diff time1 time2 nsecs) is true if time1 is nsecs seconds before time2.
The times must have the form h:m:s or h:m (24 hour form, other non-numeric
characters can be used instead of the colon)
where 0<=h<24, 0<=m<60, 0<=s<60.
Any single argument can be generated from the other two.  
Two nsecs arguments are considered equivalent if they differ by a multiple of
the number of seconds in a day.

elements.name: DATE-DIFF
elements.usage:
(date-diff date1 date2 ndays) is true if date1 is ndays before date2.
The dates must have the form y-m-d (other non-numeric characters can
be used instead of the dash) and be within the range accepted as universal
times.  Any single argument can be generated from the other two.  Ndays is
negative if date1 is after date2.

elements.name: CURRENT-TIME
elements.usage:
(current-time timezone timestring) is true if the current time in a time zone timezone hours west of Greenwich is the timestring (hh-mm-ss).
The timezone must be supplied and the timestring can be generated from it.

elements.name: CURRENT-DATE
elements.usage:
(current-date timezone datestring) is true if the current date in a time zone timezone hours west of Greenwich is the datestring (yyyy-mm-dd).
The timezone must be supplied and the datestring can be generated from it.

elements.name: CURRENT-UT
elements.usage:
(current-ut ut) is true if ut is the current universal time.
See the universaltime relation.

elements.name: UNIVERSALTIME
elements.usage:
(universaltime ut tz sec min hr day mon yr weekday) is true if ut is the number of seconds, excluding leap seconds, since the beginning of 1900 (GMT) of the time and date specified by (the numbers) sec, min, hr, day, mon, yr in a time zone that is tz hours west of Greenwich, e.g., California is either 7 or 8 depending on daylight savings. Time zones can be fractional, but must be an integral number of seconds.
Weekday is (believe it or not) zero for Monday up to 6 for Sunday.
There are two ways to generate this relation. One is to supply ut and tz. The other is to supply tz, sec, min, hr, day, mon, yr. In either case tz must be supplied and weekday is generated.
elements.description: Time as measured in seconds since some past date

elements.name: WB-PROJECT-SEARCH
elements.usage:
(wb-project-search searchstring id region country status projectname amount)

elements.name: WORLDBANK-DATA
elements.usage:
(worldbank-data id country year value) id is the id of what the World Bank calls an indicator, such as SP.POP.TOTL (meaning total population; see worldbank-indicator). The country is a country name, like Zimbabwe, the year is an integer, like 2007, and the value is a number which has to be interpreted relative to the indicator. The tuple as a whole means that the value of that indicator for the given country for the given year was the given value. There is also data for a number of regions, which are effectively treated as countries, e.g., World, or Arab World. Among other things, this means that it is not correct to add up the data for all of the countries in order to get a total for the world.
The indicators cannot be generated (that's what worldbank-indicator is for). All of the data for a given indicator can be generated. In fact, when any data for an indicator is requested, all of the data for that indicator is read and cached. (Since the data are historical, the cached values should be valid forever.) However, only a limited amount of data is cached. Therefore it is not practical (nor do we consider it to be useful) to iterate over indicators retrieving data for those indicators.
There are about 4000 indicators, but many are poorly documented and many have little useful data.
elements.description: Get data for a given indicator and country

elements.name: WORLDBANK-INDICATOR
elements.usage:
(worldbank-indicator id name doc source) describes what the World Bank calls indicators, but intuitively might better be called a statistic. All of the arguments are text strings. The id is a code with some internal structure, such as AG.CON.FERT.MT. The name amounts to short documentation, such as Fertilizer consumption (metric tons), the doc is a longer description, but sometimes NULL, and the source is the name of the data set where the data for the indicator is found. The data is all stored in the server and so is completely generable. There are about 4000 indicators, but many are poorly documented and many have little useful data.
See also worldbank-data.
elements.description: Get indicators corresponding to various metrics
